</table>
<p>Notes:</p>
<ul>
<li>The number of Peloponnesians</li>
</ul>
<p>Diodorus suggests that there were 1,000 <a href="/wiki/Laconia" title="Laconia">Lacedemonians</a> and 3,000 other Pelopennesians, for a total of 4,000. Herodotus agrees with this figure in one passage, quoting an inscription by <a href="/wiki/Simonides" title="Simonides">Simonides</a> saying there were 4,000 Peloponnesians.<sup id="cite_ref-VII228_56-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-VII228-56" title=""><span>[</span>57<span>]</span></a></sup> However, elsewhere, in the passage summarized by the above table, Herodotus tallies 3,100 Peloponnesians at Thermopylae before the battle<sup id="cite_ref-VII202_42-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-VII202-42" title=""><span>[</span>43<span>]</span></a></sup> Herodotus also reports that at Xerxes' public showing of the dead, "helots were also there for them to see",<sup id="cite_ref-VIII25_57-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-VIII25-57" title=""><span>[</span>58<span>]</span></a></sup> but he does not say how many or in what capacity they served. Thus, the difference between his two figures can be squared by supposing (without proof) that there were 900 helots (three per Spartan) present at the battle.<sup id="cite_ref-Macan_55-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Macan-55" title=""><span>[</span>56<span>]</span></a></sup> If helots were present at the battle, there is no reason to doubt that they served in their traditional role as armed retainers to individual Spartans. Alternatively, Herodotus's 'missing' 900 troops might have been <a href="/wiki/Perioeci" title="Perioeci">Perioeci</a>, and could therefore correspond to Diodorus's 1,000 Lacedemonians.<sup id="cite_ref-Macan_55-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Macan-55" title=""><span>[</span>56<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<ul>
<li>The number of Lacedemonians</li>
</ul>
<p>Further confusing the issue is Diodorus's ambiguity about whether his 1,000 Lacedemonians include the 300 Spartans. At one point he says: "<i>Leonidas, when he received the appointment, announced that only one thousand men should follow him on the campaign'</i>".<sup id="cite_ref-dsXI4_54-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dsXI4-54" title=""><span>[</span>55<span>]</span></a></sup> However, he then says that: "<i>There were, then, of the Lacedaemonians one thousand, and with them three hundred Spartiates</i>".<sup id="cite_ref-dsXI4_54-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dsXI4-54" title=""><span>[</span>55<span>]</span></a></sup> It is therefore impossible to be clearer on this point.</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Pausanias_(geographer)" title="Pausanias (geographer)">Pausanias</a>' account agrees with that of Herodotus (whom he probably read) except that he gives the number of Locrians, which Herodotus declined to estimate. Residing in the direct path of the Persian advance, they gave all the fighting men they had; according to Pausanias 6,000 men, which added to Herodotus' 5,200 would have given a force of 11,200.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58" title=""><span>[</span>59<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Many modern historians, who usually consider Herodotus more reliable,<sup id="cite_ref-Green_59-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Green-59" title=""><span>[</span>60<span>]</span></a></sup> add the 1,000 Lacedaemonians and the 900 Helots to Herodotus' 5,200 to obtain 7,100 or about 7,000 men as a standard number, neglecting Diodorus' Melians and Pausanias' Locrians.<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60" title=""><span>[</span>61<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-russel_61-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-russel-61" title=""><span>[</span>62<span>]</span></a></sup> However, this is only one approach, and many other combinations are plausible. Furthermore, the numbers changed later on in the battle when most of the army retreated and only approximately 3,000 men remained (300 Spartans, 700 Thespians, 400 Thebans, probably 900 helots and 1,000 Phocians stationed above the pass; less the casualties sustained in the previous days).<sup id="cite_ref-Green_59-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Green-59" title=""><span>[</span>60<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p><a name="Strategic_and_tactical_considerations" id="Strategic_and_tactical_considerations"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Battle_of_Thermopylae&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Strategic and tactical considerations">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Strategic and tactical considerations</span></h2>
<p>From a strategic point of view, by defending Thermopylae, the Allies were making the best possible use of their forces.<sup id="cite_ref-L248_62-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-L248-62" title=""><span>[</span>63<span>]</span></a></sup> As long as they could prevent further Persian advance into Greece, they had no requirement to seek a decisive battle, and could thus remain on the defensive. Moreover, by defending two constricted passages (Thermopylae and Artemisium), the Allies' inferior numbers became less problematic.<sup id="cite_ref-L248_62-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-L248-62" title=""><span>[</span>63<span>]</span></a></sup> Conversely, for the Persians the problem of supplying such a large army meant that the Persians could not remain in the same place for too long.<sup id="cite_ref-h285_63-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-h285-63" title=""><span>[</span>64<span>]</span></a></sup> The Persians must therefore retreat or advance; and advancing required the pass of Thermopylae to be forced.<sup id="cite_ref-h285_63-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-h285-63" title=""><span>[</span>64<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Tactically, the pass at Thermopylae was ideally suited to the Greek style of warfare.<sup id="cite_ref-L248_62-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-L248-62" title=""><span>[</span>63<span>]</span></a></sup> A <a href="/wiki/Hoplite" title="Hoplite">hoplite</a> <a href="/wiki/Phalanx_formation" title="Phalanx formation">phalanx</a> would be able to block the narrow pass with ease, with no risk of being outflanked by cavalry. In the pass, the phalanx would have been very difficult to assault for the more lightly armed Persian infantry.<sup id="cite_ref-L248_62-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-L248-62" title=""><span>[</span>63<span>]</span></a></sup> The major weak point for the Allies was the mountain track which led across the highland parallel to Thermopylae, and which would allow their position to be outflanked. Although probably unsuitable for cavalry, this path could easily be traversed by the Persian infantry (many of whom were versed in mountain warfare).<sup id="cite_ref-h288_64-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-h288-64" title=""><span>[</span>65<span>]</span></a></sup> Leonidas was made aware of this path by local people from <a href="/wiki/Trachis" title="Trachis">Trachis</a>, and he positioned a detachment of Phocian troops there in order to block this route.<sup id="cite_ref-h262_44-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-h262-44" title=""><span>[</span>45<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p><a name="Topography_of_the_battlefield" id="Topography_of_the_battlefield"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Battle_of_Thermopylae&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Topography of the battlefield">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Topography of the battlefield</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Thermopylae_map_480bc.png" class="image" title="Map of Thermopylae area with modern shoreline and reconstructed shoreline of 480 BC"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ec/Thermopylae_map_480bc.png/250px-Thermopylae_map_480bc.png" width="250" height="192" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Thermopylae_map_480bc.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Map of Thermopylae area with modern shoreline and reconstructed shoreline of 480 BC</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>At the time, the pass of Thermopylae consisted of a track along the shore of the Gulf of Malis so narrow that only one chariot could pass through at a time.<sup id="cite_ref-VII176_65-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-VII176-65" title=""><span>[</span>66<span>]</span></a></sup> On the southern side of the track stood the cliffs, while on the north side was the gulf. Along the path was a series of three constrictions, or "gates" (pylai), and at the center gate a short wall that had been erected by the Phocians in the previous century to aid in their defense against <a href="/wiki/Thessalian" title="Thessalian" class="mw-redirect">Thessalian</a> invasions.<sup id="cite_ref-VII176_65-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-VII176-65" title=""><span>[</span>66<span>]</span></a></sup> The name "Hot Gates" comes from the <a href="/wiki/Hot_spring" title="Hot spring">hot springs</a> that were located there.<sup id="cite_ref-VIII201_43-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-VIII201-43" title=""><span>[</span>44<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Today, the pass is not near the sea but is several miles inland because of sedimentation in the Gulf of Malis. The old track appears at the foot of hills around the plain, flanked by a modern road. Recent <a href="/wiki/Core_sample" title="Core sample">core samples</a> indicate that the pass was only 100 meters wide and the waters came up to the gates; "<i>Little do the visitors realize that the battle took place across the road from the monument.</i>"<sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66" title=""><span>[</span>67<span>]</span></a></sup> The pass still is a natural defensive position to modern armies, and <a href="/wiki/Commonwealth_of_Nations" title="Commonwealth of Nations">British Commonwealth</a> forces in <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a> made a <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Thermopylae_(1941)" title="Battle of Thermopylae (1941)">defense in 1941</a> against the <a href="/wiki/Nazi" title="Nazi" class="mw-redirect">Nazi</a> invasion meters from the original battle field.</p>
<ul>
<li>Maps of the region:<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67" title=""><span>[</span>68<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68" title=""><span>[</span>69<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Image of the battlefield, from the east:<a href="http://www.livius.org/a/battlefields/thermopylae/thermopylae.JPG" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.livius.org/a/battlefields/thermopylae/thermopylae.JPG" rel="nofollow">[5]</a></li>
</ul>
<p><a name="Battle" id="Battle"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Battle_of_Thermopylae&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Battle">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Battle</span></h2>
<p><a name="First_day" id="First_day"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Battle_of_Thermopylae&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: First day">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">First day</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
